    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "a2786ba3_f94ef80d",
        "filename": "util/misc/capture_context_mac.S",
        "patchSetId": 4
      },
      "lineNbr": 32,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-05-01T15:32:13Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "1. 0x90 is an x86 nop. It’s not the right pad byte for ARM text. nop on ARM is just zeroes, which is the default if you don’t give .balign or .p2align a second parameter.\n\n2. On x86, we normally align to 16 at the start of a function (.balign 16, 0x90 or .p2align 4, 0x90). But on ARM, we traditionally align just to an instruction boundary, which is .balign 4 or .p2align 2.\n\nThe canonical thing for ARM would be .p2align 2, so just use that for ARM.\n\nAs we discussed, the modern thing is to use .p2align, so if you want, you can change this one for x86 from .balign 16 to .p2align 4.",
      "revId": "a7e697763ab0bb623bec4d7baa62f9af1ddc5616",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
